   "source": [
    "# Backprojection of the Seismic Wavefield\n",
    "\n",
    "In this notebook, we use the powerful deep neural network PhaseNet [Zhu et al. 2019](https://academic.oup.com/gji/article/216/1/261/5129142) to compute waveform features that are optimized for earthquake detection and location. The backprojection is done on these waveform features rather than the waveforms themselves. The efficient core backprojection routine used by `BPMF` is implemented in our python package [`beampower`](https://github.com/ebeauce/beampower). "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

   "source": [
    "# PROGRAM PARAMETERS\n",
    "# DEVICE: is \"cpu\" or \"gpu\" depending on whether you want to use Nvidia GPUs or not\n",
    "DEVICE = \"cpu\"\n",
    "# PHASES: list of seismic phases to use for backprojection\n",
    "PHASES = [\"P\", \"S\"]\n",
    "# N_MAX_STATIONS: the maximum number of stations used for stacking (e.g. the closest to a given grid point)\n",
    "# note: this parameter is irrelevant in this example with only 8 stations, but it is important when\n",
    "# using large seismic networks\n",
    "N_MAX_STATIONS = 10\n",
    "\n",
    "NETWORK_FILENAME = \"network.csv\"\n",
    "TT_FILENAME = \"tts.h5\"\n",
    "OUTPUT_DB_FILENAME = \"raw_bp.h5\"\n",
    "DATA_FOLDER = \"preprocessed_2_12\"\n",
    "\n",
    "# PhaseNet was trained for 100Hz data, however, it shows good performances\n",
    "# for other sampling rates. Using 25Hz data causes PhaseNet to \"smooth\" in time \n",
    "# its output, which is actually good for the purpose of backprojection.\n",
    "PHASENET_SAMPLING_RATE_HZ = 100.\n",
    "UPSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION = 1\n",
    "DOWNSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION = 1\n",
    "UPSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_RELOCATION = int(PHASENET_SAMPLING_RATE_HZ/BPMF.cfg.SAMPLING_RATE_HZ)\n",
    "DOWNSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_RELOCATION = 1\n",
    "# Note for if you are adapting this tutorial to your data:\n",
    "# UPSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN and DOWNSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN need to be integers\n",
    "# if PHASENET_SAMPLING_RATE_HZ/BPMF.cfg.SAMPLING_RATE_HZ is not an integer,\n",
    "# you need to find the closest integer that is a multiple of PHASENET_SAMPLING_RATE_HZ/BPMF.cfg.SAMPLING_RATE_HZ\n",
    "# and choose DOWNSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN such that you fall back on PHASENET_SAMPLING_RATE_HZ after using resample_poly"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Compute the waveform features\n",
    "\n",
    "The goal is to compute the `waveform_features` numpy.ndarray with dimension `(n_stations, n_channels, n_times)`.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here, we demonstrate how a single-station deep neural network detector can be turned into an array detector with backprojection.\n",
    "\n",
    "*Note:* we use `phasenet` from [https://github.com/ebeauce/PhaseNet](https://github.com/ebeauce/PhaseNet) to access the wrapper module `phasenet.wrapper`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# get the data in a numpy.ndarray\n",
    "data_arr = data.get_np_array(net.stations)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "n events: 1, n stations: 8, batch size (n events x n stations): 8\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",

      "To enable them in other operations, rebuild TensorFlow with the appropriate compiler flags.\n",

      "Pred:   0%|          | 0/1 [00:00<?, ?it/s]2023-03-07 10:07:50.655547: W tensorflow/core/framework/cpu_allocator_impl.cc:82] Allocation of 552960000 exceeds 10% of free system memory.\n",

      "Pred: 100%|██████████| 1/1 [00:05<00:00,  5.52s/it]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "if ((UPSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION > 1) or (DOWNSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION > 1)):\n",
    "    data_arr = resample_poly(\n",
    "        data_arr,\n",
    "        UPSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION,\n",
    "        DOWNSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION,\n",
    "        axis=-1\n",
    "    )\n",
    "# PN_probas are time series of P-/S-wave arrival probabilities\n",
    "PN_probas, _ = PN.automatic_picking(\n",
    "    data_arr[np.newaxis, ...],\n",
    "    net.stations,\n",
    "    mini_batch_size=16,\n",
    "    format=\"ram\",\n",
    "    inter_op_parallelism_threads=n_CPUs,\n",
    "    intra_op_parallelism_threads=n_CPUs,\n",
    ")\n",
    "waveform_features = np.swapaxes(PN_probas.squeeze(), 2, 1)\n",
    "if ((UPSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION > 1) or (DOWNSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION > 1)):\n",
    "    waveform_features = resample_poly(\n",
    "        waveform_features,\n",
    "        DOWNSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION,\n",
    "        UPSAMPLING_BEFORE_PN_DETECTION,\n",
    "        axis=-1\n",
    "    )"
   ]

    "See that the number of channels in `waveform_features` is only 2. This is because `phasenet` returned a time series of P-arrival probability `waveform_features[:, 0, :]` and a time series of S-arrival probability `waveform_features[:, 1, :]`."

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Initialize the `Beamformer` instance\n",
    "\n",
    "The initialization of the `Beamformer` instance only requires the table of travel times and the corresponding source coordinates. The sampling rate is used to convert the travel time table, in seconds, to a *moveout* table, in samples. Note that the moveouts are all taken relative to the first P-wave arrival for each source."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# the core attribute of the Beamformer instance is the table of travel times\n",
    "bf = BPMF.template_search.Beamformer(\n",
    "    tts,\n",
    "    source_coords,\n",
    "    sampling_rate=BPMF.cfg.SAMPLING_RATE_HZ,\n",
    "    phases=PHASES,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Inform the `Beamformer` instance of the data and metadata\n",
    "\n",
    "Before using the `Beamformer` instance to backproject the wavefield, we need to set a number of important attributes to the instance. First, we attach the `Data` instance to the `Beamformer` instance so that `Beamformer`'s methods can read the `Data` instance's attributes. Second, we attach the `Network` instance corresponding to the set of stations that we are going to use for this backprojection.<br/>\n",
    "\n",
    "**N.B.:** The `Network` instance can be a subset of the total network represented in the travel time table! It means that you can initialize the `Beamformer` instance once and for all and then process different time periods when the operating stations might be a subset of the total network."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# attach the Data instance\n",
    "bf.set_data(data)\n",
    "# attach the Network instance\n",
    "bf.set_network(net)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Define the phase-specific weights\n",
    "\n",
    "We recall that the definition of a beam is:\n",
    "$$ b_k(t) = \\sum_{s, c, p} f_{s, c}(t + \\tau_{s, p}^{(k)}),$$\n",
    "where $k$ is the source (grid point) index, $f_{s, c}(t)$ is the waveform feature at station $s$, channel $c$ and time $t$, and $\\tau_{s, p}^{(k)}$ is the moveout at station $s$, seismic phase $p$ and source $k$. For a given $p$, the moveout is the same of all channels of the same station $s$. Therefore, the quantity $\\sum_{c} f_{s, c}(t)$ can be computed once and for all instead of re-computing it for each source.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, for a given seismic phase, say the P-wave, we may not want to use all channels. For example, we may want to use only the vertical channel, or, with the `waveform_features` previously computed with `phasenet`, we only want to use the P-arrival probability time series. Thus, the quantity we can compute once and for all is:\n",
    "$$ F_{s, p}(t) = \\sum_{c} \\alpha_{s, c, p} f_{s, c}(t).$$\n",
    "$\\alpha_{s, c, p}$ is the phase-specific weight at station $s$ and channel $c$ and for phase $p$.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this example, the appropriate phase-specific weights are:\n",
    "$$ w_{s, c=0, p=0} = 1;\\quad w_{s, c=1, p=0} = 0,$$\n",
    "$$ w_{s, c=0, p=1} = 0;\\quad w_{s, c=1, p=1} = 1.$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "The shape of weights_phases is:  (8, 2, 2)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "weights_phases = np.ones((waveform_features.shape[:-1]) + (2,), dtype=np.float32)\n",
    "weights_phases[:, 0, 1] = 0.0  # S-wave weights to zero for channel 0\n",
    "weights_phases[:, 1, 0] = 0.0  # P-wave weights to zero for channel 1\n",
    "print(\"The shape of weights_phases is: \", weights_phases.shape)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# attach the phase-specific weights to the NetworkResponse instance\n",
    "bf.set_weights(weights_phases=weights_phases)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Define the source-specific weights\n",
    "\n",
    "When using a grid covering a large geographical region, all stations may not be relevant to every source (grid point). Small earthquakes occurring at one end of the region are unlikely to be recorded by stations at the other end of the region. In order to only use the relevant data to each source, we define the source-specific weights $\\beta_{k, s}$ and modify the definition of the beam:\n",
    "$$ b_k(t) = \\sum_{s, c, p} \\beta_{k, s} \\alpha_{s, c, p} f_{s, c}(t + \\tau_{s, p}^{(k)}),$$\n",
    "$$ b_k(t) = \\sum_{s, p} \\beta_{k, s} F_{s, p}(t + \\tau_{s, p}^{(k)}).$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The source-specific weights $\\beta_{k, s}$ can be used to restrict the source-receiver distances included in the computation of $b_k(t)$, but also to downweight some stations. The default option in `BPMF` is to set to 0 all source-station weights beyond the `N_MAX_STATIONS` closest stations. In this example, we only have 8 stations and are studying a small region so all weights are 1."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "bf.set_weights_sources(N_MAX_STATIONS)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Run the backprojection\n",
    "\n",
    "We are now ready to run the backprojection at all times $t$:\n",
    "$$ b^*(t) = \\underset{k}{\\max} \\lbrace b_k(t) \\rbrace$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ k^*(t) = \\underset{k}{\\argmax} \\lbrace b_k(t) \\rbrace $$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#\n",
    "bf.backproject(waveform_features, device=DEVICE, reduce=\"max\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "After calling `bf.backproject` with `reduce=\"max\"`, we have computed $b^*(t)$ and $k^*(t)$. These can be found at `bf.maxbeam` and `bf.maxbeam_sources`.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's plot $b^*(t)$."
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Define the earthquake detections\n",
    "\n",
    "Detecting earthquakes based on the maximum beam computed above relies on a somewhat arbitrary task: defining a detection threshold. When stacking many time series, we may expect the sum to nearly be normally distributed according to the central limit theorem. However, the distribution of the maximum beam is often far from a normal distribution and the definition of a detection threshold based on gaussian p-values is not a valid approach.\n",
    "\n",
    "The detection threshold used in this example was derived purely empirically by trial-and-error, checking the quality of the detected events. We use a threshold = 2. As you will see in the following cells, this choice is quite conservative; don't hesitate playing with the threshold and lowering it.\n",
    "\n",
    "To avoid declaring multiple detections for a single event, we also define a minimum inter-event time. During the backprojection stage of `BPMF`, we do not aim at detecting all the closely occurring earthquakes of a single sequence but solely need to detect some of these earthquakes that will later allow detecting the whole sequence with template matching. Thus, we choose a minimum inter-event time of 1 minute."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Extracted 13 events.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "MINIMUM_INTEREVENT_TIME_SEC = 60.0  \n",
    "detection_threshold = 2.00 * np.ones(len(bf.maxbeam), dtype=np.float32)\n",
    "\n",
    "detections, peak_indexes, source_indexes = bf.find_detections(\n",
    "    detection_threshold, MINIMUM_INTEREVENT_TIME_SEC\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },

   "metadata": {},

   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "At this stage, we could save the metadata of each detected event and go to the next notebook, but we will first look at the waveforms of the detected events."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Extract the detected events from the continuous data\n",
    "\n",
    "Each detected earthquake is returned as an instance of the `BPMF.dataset.Event` class."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "2.99sec to read the waveforms for all 13 detections.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# event extraction parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "# PHASE_ON_COMP: dictionary defining which moveout we use to extract the waveform\n",
    "PHASE_ON_COMP = {\"N\": \"S\", \"1\": \"S\", \"E\": \"S\", \"2\": \"S\", \"Z\": \"P\"}\n",
    "# OFFSET_PHASE: dictionary defining the time offset taken before a given phase\n",
    "#               for example OFFSET_PHASE[\"P\"] = 1.0 means that we extract the window\n",
    "#               1 second before the predicted P arrival time\n",
    "OFFSET_PHASE = {\"P\": 1.0, \"S\": 4.0}\n",
    "# TIME_SHIFTED: boolean, if True, use moveouts to extract relevant windows\n",
    "TIME_SHIFTED = True\n",
    "\n",
    "t1 = give_time()\n",
    "for i in range(len(detections)):\n",
    "    detections[i].read_waveforms(\n",
    "        BPMF.cfg.TEMPLATE_LEN_SEC,\n",
    "        phase_on_comp=PHASE_ON_COMP,\n",
    "        offset_phase=OFFSET_PHASE,\n",
    "        time_shifted=TIME_SHIFTED,\n",
    "        data_folder=DATA_FOLDER,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "t2 = give_time()\n",
    "print(\n",
    "    f\"{t2-t1:.2f}sec to read the waveforms for all {len(detections):d} detections.\"\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In the following, we use the `Beamformer` method to plot the detected earthquakes (only works after calling `read_waveform` with each detection, see above cell). Because we declared in `PHASE_ON_COMP` using the S wave on the horizontal components and the P wave on the vertical components, the red vertical lines on the following plots show the predicted S-wave arrival on the horizontal components and the P-wave arrival on the vertical components."
   ]

   "source": [
    "## Store the metadata of the detected earthquakes in a database\n",
    "\n",
    "By calling the `Event.write` method for each detection, we save their metadata in a hdf5 file located at `BPMF.cfg.OUTPUT_PATH/OUTPUT_DB_FILENAME`. Each event is stored in a separate hdf5 group with name defined as `detections[i].id`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "#                 Save detections\n",
    "# ---------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "for i in range(len(detections)):\n",
    "    detections[i].write(\n",
    "        OUTPUT_DB_FILENAME,\n",
    "        db_path=BPMF.cfg.OUTPUT_PATH,\n",
    "        gid=detections[i].id\n",
    "        )"
   ]
  }
